', 'Cornelia Street Café

', 'Uncle on Sullivan Street; before World War II
', 'Douglas Goetsch; Sanford Fraser
', 'Angelo Verga is a poet and a professor. He was born in the Bronx from a Jewish mother and an Italian father. Despite his love for the Bronx, he was attracted to Greenwich Village. There, he spent his formative years and grew as a poet. During the 1960s up until the late 1990s, there was still an art scene in the neighborhood. The place was nurturing, edgy and even dangerous. There was a sense of community. After teaching and taking a few writing courses at The New School, he started publishing his poems. During the 1990s, he became a significant member of the poetry circuit. He performed his work at famous places like the Nuyorican Poet’s Café and the Cornelia Street Café. Many of his friends are active poets such as Douglas Goetsch and Sanford Fraser who are local residents. He wishes the Village had kept its ‘character’ and discusses recent changes in the neighborhood. 

Additional controlled search terms: Washington Square; bookstores; social life and customs; nightlife; small business; writers. 

