', '1970 to time of interview
', 'Westbeth Artists'' Housing
', '', '', 'Lucienne Weinberger and her husband were among the first people to move into Westbeth Artists’ Housing in 1970. She is interviewed by a neighbor. 

Residents of the new Westbeth apartments were urban pioneers. Located close to the waterfront the immediate area consisted of vacant warehouses, an abandoned elevated highway and rotting piers. But just 2 blocks to the east there was a wealthy neighborhood full of townhouses that reminded Lucienne of Paris. 

The waterfront area began to change in the mid 1980s. Many warehouses were converted into residential lofts. Chelsea Piers was one of the first construction projects devoted to entertainment. The West Side Highway was dismantled and replaced by Hudson River Park. 

Real estate development is transforming New York City. Buildings are higher and closer together and the neighborhood has lost some of its original character. 

Additional controlled search terms: nightlife; restaurants. 
Additional key words: Bell Telephone Laboratory; Chelsea Market. 
', 'https://s3.amazonaws.com/oral-history/audio/weinberger_lucienne.mp3', 0, 'weinberger_lucienne.jpg', NULL, '[]', '2014-04-24 17:09:08.604638', '2015-04-30 20:52:42.147415', 1, 0, 1, '');
