', '', '', 'John Noble Wilford is an accomplished journalist who spent 45 years at The New York Times. His scientific writing includes coverage of the Apollo 11 moon landing. 

In 1970 he and his wife bought a small house on West 10th Street that was built in 1833 when Greenwich Village was a rural area. John researched the history of his house and through recollections of people, streets, popular places and events from the 1800s through Hurricane Sandy and 9/11 he provides a clear picture of the neighborhood. 

John notes that real estate development is responsible for many changes and he also shares his observations of what it means to live in a low-rise community. John and his wife are comfortable living in the Village because it doesn’t tower over their lives. 

