', '1977 to 2009
', '7th Avenue South at Bleecker Street
', '', '', 'Hara Seltzer grew up in Brooklyn. In 1977 she moved to a walk-up apartment on the corner of 7th Avenue South & Bleecker Street and stayed there for 35 years. 

Hara is a visual artist. She met a lot of unconventional people in Greenwich Village. The low rents allowed people to work fewer days and have more time to follow other interests such as painting or ballet. 

Hara enjoyed the neighborhood social life. There were many small bars and restaurants where people went to hang out. 

The Village has changed a lot. Bleecker Street was full of antique stores and jewelry makers but high fashion clothing stores have replaced them. The area is historic but it is really for tourists now. 

Additional controlled search terms: artists; buildings; nightlife; small business. 

Additional key words: 9 Jones; Martin Scorsese; street fair. 
', 'https://s3.amazonaws.com/oral-history/audio/seltzer_hara.mp3', 0, 'seltzer_hara.jpg_001_copy.jpg', NULL, '[]', '2014-04-24 16:59:27.480122', '2015-04-23 20:07:12.886349', 1, 0, 1, '');
