', '1934 to time of interview
', '71 Washington Square South;14 West 10th Street', '', '', 'Penny Blum has lived on Washington Square Park since the mid-1930s. She is interviewed by a friend. 

Through the early 1970s Penny lived in an apartment building on the site where New York University’s Bobst Library now stands. She then moved to the north side of the park. 

NYU has taken over Greenwich Village, buying and demolishing properties for new construction. Penny remembers a time when there were many townhouses and no high-rise buildings in the neighborhood. 

Her social life centered on the coffee houses and bars along MacDougal Street, many of which featured live folk music. 8th Street and Bleecker Street were full of bookstores and shops with unique handmade items but they are all gone. 

Additional controlled search terms: nightlife; real estate development; restaurants; small business. 
', 'https://s3.amazonaws.com/oral-history/audio/Blum%2C+Penny_FINALEDIT.mp3', 0, 'blum_penny.jpg', NULL, NULL, '2014-04-04 20:41:48.881703', '2015-05-21 15:12:08.251386', 1, 0, 1, '');
