Activist Jane Jacobs was a great influence and, concerned about maintaining the intimate feel of the area, he became a community leader opposed to plans of developers such as Robert Moses. 

Arthur saw the end of back room decision-making in favor of a process that allows residents a say in local government. He discusses local political clubs and elected officials. 

He was appointed member of the Community Board (CB) and served as chairman of two committees: Waterfront and Traffic & Transportation. The CB received constant applications to build new roads or change old streets. Many of these proposals were unpopular and were defeated, sometimes after long legal battles.

Although the Village continues to change, Arthur has welcomed the opportunity to  preserve the neighborhood. 

Additional controlled search terms: buildings; politicians; real estate development; social conditions. 
Additional key words: West Side Highway; Westway. 
