', '', 'Cynthia Crane is a singer/songwriter/producer/activist from a third generation New York family. She is interviewed by a neighbor. 

Cynthia talks about the businesses her relatives owned in the late 1800s. She and her husband theater director Ted Story bought a brownstone on West 11th Street where they lived for over 40 years. When they arrived in 1968 there was a lot of crime but also families with children. 

Greenwich Village was the first neighborhood in the city to be landmarked but the battles over real estate development never stop. 

Cynthia organized a neighborhood association and held block parties. She describes the early Halloween Parades. 

During the AIDS crisis Cynthia performed songs for patients at St. Vincent’s hospital and in their homes. 

